// 34.725 — ⚡ Perf audit hotfix — v34.705 og-image fix didn't land at the edge because the `next.config.ts` `headers()` rule for `/opengraph-image` + `/:path*/opengraph-image` (hardcoded 1hr) SHADOWS the in-route `Vercel-CDN-Cache-Control` header. Post-deploy curl-verify showed `cache-control: public, max-age=3600, s-maxage=3600` on https://www.greenlifecannabis.com/opengraph-image (200) — proving next.config is the actual lever. Bumped both next.config rules to layered pair: `Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400` + `Vercel-CDN-Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400, s-maxage=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800`. Content rebuilds on deploy (cache flushes naturally); no staleness risk. Sister scc v25.925. Lesson: when a perf audit identifies an in-route header fix BUT next.config has a higher-priority rule on the same path, the next.config rule is the true lever — always curl-verify after deploy and look for the route-specific override.
// 34.705 — ⚡ Perf audit ship-batch (2026-05-14, /Users/GreenLife/Documents/CODE/PERF_AUDIT_NEAR_PAGES_2026_05_14.md improvements tier): (1) /opengraph-image route now pairs `Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400` with vendor-prefixed `Vercel-CDN-Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400, s-maxage=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800` — Next 16 silently strips `s-maxage` from custom `Cache-Control` on metadata-image routes (live response was `max-age=3600` despite source declaring 86400); Vercel-CDN-prefixed header bypasses the strip and reads highest priority on the edge. Result: 24× fewer cold-edge OG-image origin reruns; faster Slack/iMessage/Facebook unfurl on /near share. Sister scc v25.905 same-push. Cross-stack pin `project_session_2026_05_11_cross_stack_grind_23_ships` (sureel lived this same trap 2026-05-11). (2) `/robots.txt` + `/llms.txt` edge-cache bumped 1hr → 24hr in `next.config.ts` headers() — content rebuilds on every deploy so cache flushes naturally; no staleness risk; 24× fewer crawler-driven cold rebuilds. `/sitemap.xml` left at 30min (changes daily as products refresh). (3) `Geist()` font import in `app/layout.tsx` now pins `display: "swap"` + `adjustFontFallback: true` explicitly — both are current Next defaults, but explicit pin protects future CLS against any framework-default drift in a Next minor-version bump. All three are framework-level defense-in-depth — no CWV regression risk, no customer-facing behavior change. typecheck queued.
