// 7.825 — 📱 iOS PWA polish — explicit `metadata.icons.apple` declaration in `app/layout.tsx`. Next 16 doesn't auto-emit `<link rel="apple-touch-icon">` when the icon is served by a route handler (we use `app/apple-icon.png/route.tsx` for dynamic ImageResponse generation, not a static binary). Pre-fix: HTML `<head>` had `<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-title" content="Green Life">` (set up correctly via `appleWebApp.title`) but NO `apple-touch-icon` link — iOS Safari "Add to Home Screen" falls back to a generic globe icon. The route already serves 200 + 180×180 PNG (the GL gradient logo); this metadata change just points iOS at it. Verified: `curl -I /apple-icon.png` returns 200 + correct Content-Type. Sister scc v8.945 (same fix). Single-block addition; tsc clean.
// 7.805 — ⚡ Perf — `loading="lazy"` added on 4 below-fold `<img>` tags that were missing it: `app/about/page.tsx` (team grid member photo, 48×48), `app/community/page.tsx` (community grid photo, 48×48), `app/our-story/page.tsx` (founders/staff photo, 56×56 round), `components/VendorAdSlot.tsx` (vendor ad, ~160min h). VendorAdSlot fix is conditional via new `loading` prop (default `"lazy"`) — pre-commit Explore review caught that `homepage_top` slot at app/page.tsx:169 renders BEFORE the hero (above-fold on desktop), so that one usage now passes `loading="eager"` explicitly. The other 3 VendorAdSlot usages (`homepage_under_hero`, `homepage_under_brands`, `cross_store_promo`) inherit the lazy default — those are all far below-fold. Net effect: every below-fold image lazy-loads + the one above-fold spot remains eager. Sister scc v8.925 (mirror fix: 2 sites + same conditional `loading` prop). Single-attribute add per file; tsc clean. Audit recipe: `for f in $(grep -rln "<img" app/ components/); do count_img=$(grep -c "<img" "$f"); count_lazy=$(awk "/<img/,/\/?>/" "$f" | grep -c "loading="); [ "$count_img" != "$count_lazy" ] && echo "$f: img=$count_img lazy=$count_lazy"; done`.
// 7.785 — 🔗 JSON-LD `OrderAction.target` in app/layout.tsx now points at `${STORE.website}/menu` (was `${STORE.website}/order`). Per Doug operating-principle: customer CTAs on the cannabis sites point to `/menu` only — not iHeartJane direct, not /order. Pre-fix the Google rich-result OrderAction button on the LocalBusiness card would have routed click-throughs to /order which proxy.ts 307-redirects to /menu (extra redirect hop, wasted Google crawl-citation, inconsistent with sitemap rule that already removed /order at v7.665). Now SERP citation = canonical /menu page directly, no redirect. Sister scc v8.905 (also fixed bare `/menu` → absolute URL `${STORE.website}${STORE.shopUrl}` so the same `OrderAction.target` is structured-data-parser valid on both sites). Single-line edit; no human-visitor behavior change. tsc clean.
// 7.765 — 🌍 SEO sitemap-image hygiene — 200-or-bust audit found 2 vendor logo URLs in glw `vendors.logoUrl` (Postgres) returning non-2xx: `the420bar.com/.../420-logo-alpha.png` (404 / WP upload removed; vendor = Evergreen Herbal) + `agrocouture.com/.../Agro-Couture_Logo-gold.png` (202 / SiteGround captcha challenge — Google bot blocked). Both pre-fix appeared as `<image:image><image:loc>` entries in `/sitemap.xml`. Customer impact: zero (both brands have no recent sales — excluded from `/brands` render by the `brands_with_recent_sales` 365d gate). Google impact: small — search engines de-prioritize sitemaps with broken image entries + may flag the parent /brands/<slug> URL if image:image is the canonical preview. Fix: added `BROKEN_LOGO_URLS` Set in `app/sitemap.ts` that the per-brand `images:` field filters against. Brand page entry itself stays in sitemap (real page); only the dead image hint drops. Doug-action queued (memory pin): update `vendors.logoUrl` in glw Postgres to working source — self-hosted under `/public/images/brands/` is safest going forward — then remove URL from the Set. Discovered by 200-or-bust audit per memory `feedback_grind_past_tapped_scoreboard_2026_05_08`. tsc clean.
// 7.745 — 🛡️ PII-leak round 4: `app/api/quiz/capture/route.ts` had two leaks the v7.725 wrapper-source fix didn't catch — they don't go through `lib/email.ts`. Line 200 was the D+0 dispatch catch around `dispatchD0Welcome` (Resend errors echo recipient email + sender domain in `err.message`: &ldquo;Invalid email address: ...&rdquo; / &ldquo;Sender domain not verified&rdquo;). Line 209 was the surrounding INSERT catch — Drizzle wraps Postgres errors and the message can echo the conflicting row data (`duplicate key violates unique constraint (email)=(alice@example.com)`). Both rewritten as `err=${err instanceof Error ? err.name : "unknown"}`. The pre-fix comment on the inner catch even said &ldquo;Log without the recipient&rdquo; — the promise existed; the formatter didn't deliver it. Sister of inv v314.405 birthday-sms + quiz-nurture pattern (the latter pending Wen prod queue). Discovered by /loop sister-fix sweep across customer-touching routes after the orders/profile/push routes were verified clean. tsc clean.
// 7.725 — 🛡️ PII-leak hardening at the email-wrapper source: `lib/email.ts:106` was logging + returning the full Resend SDK error message (`e.message`), which can echo recipient addresses ("domain not verified for foo@example.com" / "rate limited 3000/day for foo@example.com"). All callers (welcome-email, quiz-nurture-email, order-confirmation-email, admin actions) propagate `result.error` to their own `console.error` template — so the leak surfaced 4× in this repo + 4× in scc. **Fix at the source:** the wrapper now logs + returns `e.name` only (class identifier — `validation_error`, `rate_limit_exceeded`, `Error`). Every caller's existing `${result.error}` template now logs the safe class name, no caller-side edits needed. Sister scc v8.865 same-file fix. Sister of inv `lib/email.ts` pattern + the cross-repo PII-leak hardening sweep (~120 fixes earlier this session). tsc clean.
